1 (b) A provision of this section permitting the General Assembly to
2 exempt property from taxation also permits the General Assembly to
3 exercise its legislative power to enact property tax deductions and
4 credits for the property. The General Assembly may impose reasonable
5 filing requirements for an exemption, deduction, or credit.
6 (c) The General Assembly may exempt from property taxation any
7 property in any of the following classes:
8 (1) Property being used for municipal, educational, literary,
9 scientific, religious, or charitable purposes.
10 (2) Tangible personal property other than property being held as
11 an investment.
12 (3) Intangible personal property.
13 (4) Tangible property, including curtilage, used as a principal
14 place of residence by an:
15 (A) owner of the property;
16 (B) individual who is buying the tangible property under a
17 contract; or
18 (C) individual who has a beneficial interest in the owner of the
19 tangible property.
20 (d) The General Assembly may exempt any motor vehicles, mobile
21 homes (not otherwise exempt under this section), airplanes, boats,
22 trailers, or similar property, provided that an excise tax in lieu of the
23 property tax is substituted therefor.
24 (e) This subsection applies to property taxes first due and payable
25 in 2012 and thereafter. The following definitions apply to subsection
26 (f): this section:
27 (1) "Other residential property" means tangible property (other
28 than tangible property described in subsection (c)(4)) that is used
29 for residential purposes.
30 (2) "Agricultural land" means land devoted to agricultural use.
31 (3) "Other real property" means real property that is not tangible
32 property described in subsection (c)(4), is not other residential
33 property, and is not agricultural land.
34 (4) "Taxing jurisdiction" means the geographic boundaries in
35 which a unit of local government is authorized by law to
36 impose ad valorem property taxes.
37 (5) "Unit of local government" means a county, city, or town.
38 (f) This subsection applies to property taxes first due and payable in
39 2012 and thereafter. The General Assembly shall, by law, limit a
40 taxpayer's property tax liability as follows:
41 (1) A taxpayer's property tax liability on tangible property
42 described in subsection (c)(4) may not exceed one percent (1%)
2026 SJ 3—SJ 9608/DI 120

